===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

{{Han compound|止|凵|ls=ic|t1=foot|t2=cave}} – to step out of a cave; to exit. Compare {{och-l|*各}}.

By the {{w|Qin dynasty}}, the character has lost its original shape. Based on the distorted form, ''{{w|Shuowen}}'' mistakenly interprets the character as a pictogram of a plant ({{och-l|*屮}}) growing outwards.

===Etymology 1===
STEDT derives this word as a cognate of {{noncog|tbq-pro|*sV-tok|*s-twak|t=to come or go out; to emerge}}; compare {{cog|my|ထွက်|t=to go or come out; to produce or yield; to leave}}, {{cog|tbq-lob-pro|*ʔ-twakᴴ||to come or got out; to emerge}}, {{cog|tbq-kuk-pro|*tshuak-I}}, {{m|tbq-kuk-pro|*tshuaʔ-II||to come out; to emerge; to appear}}. But virtually all Old Chinese reconstructions of this word nowadays are completely phonetically incompatible with this etymon; this comparison should be rejected. <!-- This term may have been conflated with a descendant from {{noncog|sit-pro|*m-(t/d)u|t=nephew; descendant}} – whence the {{noncog|my|တူ|t=nephew}} – a sense no longer productive but was mentioned in the glossary book ''{{w|Erya}}'', {{circa2|2nd century {{BCE}}|short=y}}. ({{zh-ref|STEDT}}) -->

Alternatively, {{zh-ref|Sagart (1999)}} and {{zh-ref|Baxter and Sagart (2014)}} suggest that this word is related to other words that express extraction, such as {{och-l|掘|to dig out|tr=*[ɡ]ut}}, and reconstruct the {{cog|och|-}} with an intransitivizing prefix ''*t-''.

